ya County]]\n{{Baranya-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pettend"}
{"title_page": "I Know What You Did Last Summer", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = I Know What You Did Last Summer\n| image          = I Know What You Did Last Summer.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jim Gillespie (director)|Jim Gillespie]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Neal H. Moritz]]\n* [[Erik Feig]]\n* Stokely Chaffin\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[Kevin Williamson (screenwriter)|Kevin Williamson]]\n| based on       = ''[[I Know What You Did Last Summer (novel)|I Know What You Did Last Summer]]''<br/>by [[Lois Duncan]]\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jennifer Love Hewitt]]\n* [[Sarah Michelle Gellar]]\n* [[Ryan Phillippe]]\n* [[Freddie Prinze Jr.]]\n* [[Johnny Galecki]]\n* [[Bridgette Wilson]]\n}}<!--PER POSTER BLOCK-->\n| music          = [[John Debney]]\n| cinematography = [[Denis Crossan]]\n| editing        = Steve Mirkovich\n| studio         = [[Mandalay Entertainment]]<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members//catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=60793|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer|work=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n| distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]<ref name=\"afi\" />\n| released       = {{filmdate|1997|10|17|ref1={{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=182}}}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $17 million<ref name=\"numbers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1997/IKNOW.php |title=I Know What You Did Last Summer - Box Office Data |work=The Numbers |accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref>{{sfn|Harper|2004|p=26}}\n| gross          = $125.2 million<ref name=\"numbers\" />\n}}\n\n'''''I Know What You Did Last Summer''''' is a  1997 American [[slasher film]] directed by [[Jim Gillespie (director)|Jim Gillespie]], written by [[Kevin Williamson (screenwriter)|Kevin Williamson]], and starring [[Jennifer Love Hewitt]], [[Sarah Michelle Gellar]], [[Ryan Phillippe]], and [[Freddie Prinze Jr.]]. Loosely based on [[I Know What You Did Last Summer (novel)|the 1973 novel of the same name]] by [[Lois Duncan]] and is the first installment in [[I Know What You Did Last Summer (film series)|''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' trilogy]]. The film centers on four young friends who are stalked by a hook-wielding killer one year after covering up a car accident in which they killed a man. The film also draws inspiration from the [[urban legend]] known as [[the Hook]].\n\nAfter having written ''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]'' (released the year prior), Williamson was approached to adapt Duncan's source novel by producer [[Erik Feig]]. Where Williamson's screenplay for ''Scream'' contained prominent elements of [[satire]] and self-referentiality, his adaptation of ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' reworked the novel's central plot to resemble a straightforward 1980s-era slasher film.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=183}} Shot on location in California and [[North Carolina]] in the spring of 1997, ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' was released theatrically in North America on October 17, 1997. It received mixed reviews from critics but was commercially successful, grossing $125 million worldwide on a budget of $17 million, and remaining number 1 at the U.S. [[box office]] for three consecutive weeks. It was also nominated for and won multiple awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0119345/awards |title=I Know What You Did Last Summer - Awards |publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]}}</ref>\n\nThe film was followed by two sequels, ''[[I Still Know What You Did Last Summer]]'' (1998) and ''[[I'll Always Know What You Did Last Summer]]'' (2006). ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' has also been parodied and referenced in popular culture,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Wayans Brothers' Comedy Style A Hit In 'Scary Movie' |journal=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]] |volume=98 |page=58 |date=August 14, 2000}}</ref> and credited alongside ''Scream'' with revitalizing the [[slasher film|slasher genre]] in the 1990s.{{sfn|Shary|2012|p=62}}\n\n==Plot==\nOn the [[Fourth of July]] in [[Southport, North Carolina]], Julie James and her friends Ray Bronson, Helen Shivers, and Barry Cox drive to the beach after attending a party. While driving along a coastal byway, they accidentally hit a pedestrian. Julie's friend Max passes by them on the road. Julie reassures Max that everything is all right, and he leaves. After some arguing, the group decides to dispose of the body, dumping it in the water. They agree to never discuss the incident again.\n\nA year later, Julie returns home from her college in [[Boston]] for the summer. Since the incident, the friends have gone their separate ways. Julie receives a letter with no return address, stating, \"I know what you did last summer!\" Disturbed, Julie tracks down Helen, who has returned to Southport to work at her family's department store after a failed attempt at an acting career in New York City. The girls take the note to Barry, who immediately suspects Max as he was the only person there that night. They confront Max on the docks, and Barry threatens him with a hook, even though Max claims he has no idea what Barry is talking about. Julie meets Ray, who is now working as a fisherman; he unsuccessfully tries to reconcile with her. Later, Max is killed by a figure in a [[raincoat|rain slicker]] wielding the same hook. Barry discovers a note in his gym locker saying, \"I know.\" He is then ambushed by the same assailant driving Barry's car.\n\nMeanwhile, as Ray still suspects Max, Julie researches newspaper articles which lead her to believe the man they ran over was a local named David Egan. Helen and Julie go to visit with David's sister Missy at her home. Missy explains to them that their family was devastated by David's death; she also mentions that a friend of David's named Billy Blue also visited her to pay his last respects. Later that night, the killer sneaks into Helen's house, cuts off most of her hair while she sleeps, and writes \"Soon\" in lipstick on her vanity mirror.\n\nThe following morning, Julie finds Max's corpse wearing Barry's stolen jacket in the trunk of her car. When she calls the others, the body is missing. Julie, Helen, and Barry confront Ray about the recent events. Ray claims to have received a threatening letter as well. Julie goes back to visit Missy, while Barry and Helen go to participate in the Fourth of July parade. Missy reveals David allegedly committed suicide out of guilt for the death of his girlfriend Susie in a car accident and shows David's suicide note to Julie. As the writing matches that of the note she received, Julie realizes it was not a suicide note, but a death threat.\n\nAt the Croaker Beauty Pageant, Helen witnesses Barry being murdered on the balcony. She rushes upstairs with a police officer but finds no sign of the killer or Barry. The officer escorts Helen home, but the killer lures him into an alley and murders him. Helen flees to her nearby family store, where her sister Elsa is closing for the night. The killer enters the store and murders Elsa. Helen is chased to the third floor of the building and escapes through a window, falling to a long alleyway. She manages to run toward the street, but the killer stops her and slashes her to death, despite defending herself, her screams being drowned out by the sound of the oncoming parade.\n\nJulie finds an article mentioning Susie's father, Ben Willis, and realizes that Ben was the man they ran over, moments after he had killed David to avenge his daughter. She then goes to the docks to tell Ray, but he refuses to believe her. Julie notices Ray's boat is called ''Billy Blue'' and runs away. Ben appears, knocking Ray unconscious, and invites Julie to hide on his boat. On the boat, she finds photos and articles about her friends and her, and pictures of Susie. Ben's boat leaves the docks, and he begins tormenting Julie, chasing her below deck; there, she uncovers the bodies of Helen and Barry in the boat's ice box. Ray regains consciousness and steals a motorboat to rescue Julie. He ultimately uses the [[rigging]] to sever Ben's hand and send him overboard. When Julie and Ray are questioned by the police, they deny knowing why Ben attempted to kill them, but they are relieved not to have actually killed anyone the previous summer, and reconcile.\n\nA year later, Julie is in college in [[Boston]]. As she enters the shower, she notices the words \"I still know\" on the mirror. Moments later, the fisherman crashes through it as Julie screams in horror.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Jennifer Love Hewitt]] as Julie James\n* [[Sarah Michelle Gellar]] as Helen Shivers\n* [[Ryan Phillippe]] as Barry Cox\n* [[Freddie Prinze Jr.]] as Ray Bronson\n* [[Bridgette Wilson]] as Elsa Shivers\n* [[Anne Heche]] as Missy Egan\n* [[Muse Watson]] as Ben Willis/The Fisherman\n* [[Johnny Galecki]] as Max Neurick\n* [[Stuart Greer]] as Officer Caporizo\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and writing===\n''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' was a screenplay penned by Kevin Williamson several years beforehand, which was then rushed into production by Columbia Pictures upon the success of the Williamson-written ''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]'' (1996).<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.moviefone.com/2017/10/17/i-know-what-you-did-last-summer-movie-trivia/| title=14 Things You Never Know About 'I Know What You Did Last Summer'| author=Susman, Gary|work=MovieFone| date=October 17, 2017| access-date=February 19, 2018}}</ref> It was based on the [[I Know What You Did Last Summer (novel)|1973 novel of the same name]] by [[Lois Duncan]],{{sfn|Fahy|2010|p=248}} a youth-oriented suspense novel about four young people who are involved in a [[hit-and-run]] accident involving a young boy.<ref name=now/> Producer [[Erik Feig]] pitched the idea of a screen adaptation to [[Mandalay Entertainment]], and subsequently appointed Williamson to retool the core elements of Duncan's novel, rendering a screenplay more akin to a 1980s [[slasher film]].{{sfn|Harper|2004|p=26}}<ref name=now>{{cite av media|people=Gillis, Michael (prod., dir.)|medium=Documentary short|title=Now I Know What You Did Last Summer|year=2008|format=Blu-ray|work=I Know What You Did Last Summer|publisher=Sony Pictures Home Entertainment}}</ref> Inspired by his father, who had been a commercial fisherman, Williamson changed the setting of the novel to a small fishing village, and made the villain a hook-wielding fisherman.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=183}}\n\nThe killer's arming of himself with a hook is a reference to the [[urban legend]] \"[[The Hook]],\" which the four main characters recount at the beginning of the film around a campfire.<ref name=now/> According to Williamson, he wrote the scene as a way of indicating what was to come: \"Basically what I was doing was I was setting the framework to say, 'All right, audience: That's that legend. Now here's a new one.'\"<ref name=now/> Unlike Williamson's screenplay for the film's contemporary, ''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]'' (1996), which incorporated [[satire]] of the slasher film, ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' was written more as a straightforward slasher film.<ref name=now/>  Gillespie commented in 2008: \"The joy of this film for me as a filmmaker was in taking [the] elements that we've seen before, and saying to the audience: 'Here's something you've seen before'\u2014knowing that they're saying 'We've seen this before'\u2014and still getting them to jump.\"<ref name=now/> Gillespie also claimed that he felt Williamson's screenplay did not resemble a \"slasher horror movie,\" and that he saw it rather as simply \"a really good story\" with a [[morality]] tale embedded within it.<ref name=now/>\n\n===Pre-production===\nAccording to producer Stokely Chaffin, the producers sought out actors who were \"beautiful, but likable.\"<ref name=now/> Director Gillespie recalled that, though he had been unfamiliar with the screenplay's source material, that \"roughly 60 to 65%\" of the young women auditioning had read the novel as children.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:08:46)</ref> Jennifer Love Hewitt, who at the time was mainly known for her role on the television series ''[[Party of Five]]'', was cast in the lead of Julie James based on her \"ability to project vulnerability,\" which the producers, director Gillespie, and writer Williamson unanimously agreed upon.<ref name=now/> Initially, Hewitt was considered for the role of Helen.<ref name=now/> For the role of Barry, the crew had envisioned an actor with a \"{{convert|6|ft|2|in|abbr=on}} [[quarterback]]\" appearance, as the character had been written as an intimidating figure.<ref name=now/> Ryan Phillipe was ultimately cast in the part based on his audition, despite the fact that he was not as physically tall as the script had called for.<ref name=now/> Director Gillespie chose Freddie Prinze Jr. for the role of Ray, because he felt Prinze himself had an \"everyman\" quality much like the character.<ref name=now/>\n\nSarah Michelle Gellar was the last of the lead performers to be cast in the role of Helen.<ref name=now/> Like Hewitt, Gellar was also known to American audiences at the time for her roles in television, primarily as the titular [[Buffy Summers]] on ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]''.<ref name=now/> Gillespie commented on casting Gellar: \"I wanted an actress that had a warmth to her, but could still come off as being a bitch.\"<ref name=now/> For the supporting role of Missy, Gillespie sought an actress with significant screen presence, as the character, despite appearing in only two scenes, is central to several major plot points.<ref name=now/> Anne Heche was cast in the role, which she recalled as being two days' worth of work that required her to \"be scary.\"<ref name=now/>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Kolmer2.jpg|thumb|The cliff and rock shown at the beginning of the film, shot at Kolmer Gulch near [[Jenner, California]]]]\nScottish director Jim Gillespie was hired to direct the film after being suggested by writer Williamson.<ref name=\"now\" /> Star Hewitt would later state in 2008 that Gillespie was to date her \"favorite director [she's] ever worked with.\"<ref name=\"now\" /> Principal photography began on March 31, 1997{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}} and took place over a period of ten weeks<ref name=\"tenweeks\">[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:08:12)</ref> throughout the late spring-early summer of 1997.{{efn-lr|Gillespie notes in his 1998 audio commentary for the film that the California-shot scenes were filmed in June 1997.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:10:28)</ref> In the same commentary, he states that the shoot lasted ten weeks.<ref name=tenweeks/> According to Adam Rockoff, principal photography commenced on March 31, 1997.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}}}} Approximately seven weeks of the ten-week shoot took place at night, which Gillespie says was difficult for the cast and crew, and also created commotion in primary small-town locations in which they shot.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}} Gillespie devised a color scheme with cinematographer [[Denis Crossan]] which was marked by heavy [[blue]]s throughout, and a notable lack of bright colors.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:24:27)</ref> \n[[File:KolmerCurve.jpg|thumb|The blind curve where the car accident occurs early in the film, shot at Kolmer Gulch near [[Jenner, California]]]]\nFor the beginning of the film, coastal areas of [[Sonoma County, California]] stood in for North Carolina, where the film is set. The opening shots of the sun setting on a rugged coast were filmed at Kolmer Gulch, just north of the town of [[Jenner, California|Jenner]], on [[California State Route 1|Highway 1]].<ref name=locations>{{cite web| url=http://www.movie-locations.com/movies/i/I_Know_What_You_Did_Summer.html#.WoulM3tFzIU| title=Filming Locations for 'I Know What You Did Last Summer'| work=Movie-Locations.com| access-date=February 19, 2018}}</ref> The car crash scene was also filmed on Highway 1 in the same area. The scene in which the four friends are seated around a campfire on the beach next to a wrecked boat was inspired by a painting Gillespie had seen in a reference book; to achieve the image, the art department purchased an old boat in [[Bodega Bay]], cut it in half, and placed it at the beach location.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:09:58)</ref>\n[[File:Southport from the Water.JPG|thumb|The majority of the film was set in [[Southport, North Carolina]]. ]]\nThe remaining scenes were filmed primarily around the town of [[Southport, North Carolina|Southport]], [[North Carolina]].<ref name=locations/> Specific sites included the Amuzu Theater, where the beauty pageant is held, the Old Yacht Basin and Southport Fish Company.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.southport-oakisland.com/listing/i-know-what-you-did-last-summer-1997.html| title=I Know What You Did Last Summer (1997)| publisher= Southport-OakIsland.com| access-date=February 19, 2018}}</ref> Julie's house is on Short Street just north of Southport Marina.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.southporttimes.com/featured/200407.html| title=Movies Filmed in Southport, North Carolina| work=Southport Times| access-date=February 19, 2018}}</ref> The daytime sequences shot on the marina show multiple vessels traversing the water; though real vessels, the boat traffic was orchestrated by a marine traffic coordinator to make the waterway appear lively.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:36:57)</ref> The Shivers Department Store setting in the film was discovered on location in Southport by director Gillespie, who was so impressed by the location that he reworked elements of the script in order to incorporate it into the film; it eventually became the primary setting for Helen's extended chase sequence with the killer.<ref name=now/> The exterior sequences of Julie's Boston college campus were in fact shot at [[Duke University]],<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:24:51)</ref> while the hospital sequence was filmed at Southport's [[Dosher Memorial Hospital]] in an unused wing of the hospital.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:43:00)</ref>\n\nThe final sequence on the boat was shot on an actual water-bound vessel on the [[Cape Fear River]], which proved difficult for the actors and crew.<ref name=now/> According to Gillespie, the filmmakers nearly lost the boat while attempting to dock it due to the volatile waters, after which they were forced to leave and shoot other footage until the following day.<ref name=now/>\n\n===Post-production===\nGillespie chose to film virtually no onscreen blood as he did not want the film to be overly gratuitous in terms of violence.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}}<ref name=now/> The scene in which Elsa has her throat slashed while standing against a glass door had originally been shot from behind without any blood appearing on the glass. However, producer Feig worried that the scene appeared \"medically impossible,\" after which Gillespie re-shot it (post-principal photography) with a visual effect of blood spattering across the glass.<ref name=now/> Upon test screenings of the film, Gillespie and the producers decided that a death sequence needed to occur earlier in the film to establish a sense of legitimate danger for the main characters.<ref name=now/> The scene in which Max is murdered in the crab factory was subsequently filmed and implemented into the final cut to achieve this (in the original script, his character was not killed).<ref name=now/>\n\nThe original ending of the film featured a sequence in which Julie receives an [[email]] reading: \"I Still Know.\"{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}} This ending was scrapped for the more dramatic ending featured in the final cut of the film, in which Julie finds the same message scrawled on a shower stall just before the killer comes crashing through the glass.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}} This footage was also shot after principal photography, on a soundstage next-door to where Hewitt was filming ''Party of Five''.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (1:35:29)</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Marketing===\nIn anticipation of the film's release, distributor [[Columbia Pictures]] began a summer marketing campaign that presented the film as being \"From the creator of ''Scream''.\"{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}} [[Miramax|Miramax Films]] subsequently filed a lawsuit against Columbia, arguing the claim was inaccurate as the director of ''Scream'' was [[Wes Craven]], not Williamson.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}} The week following the film's theatrical release, a federal judge awarded Miramax an [[injunction]] requiring that Columbia remove the claim from their advertising campaign.<ref>{{cite web|work=Variety|url=https://variety.com/1997/biz/news/miramax-reigns-in-court-1116674228/|title=Miramax reigns in court|date=October 20, 1997|accessdate=April 8, 2018|author=Karon, Paul}}</ref> Williamson had requested its removal prior after seeing it on a theater poster.<ref name=lawsuit>{{cite web|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/mar/07/business/fi-26323|title=Miramax Wins 'Scream' Claim Against Sony|author=Bates, James|date=March 7, 1998|accessdate=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMiramax won a subsequent lawsuit against Columbia during a March 1998 hearing. In a press release, executive [[Bob Weinstein]] noted plans to \"vigorously pursue\" damage claims against Columbia Pictures for their use of the claim.<ref name=lawsuit/>\n\n===Box office===\n''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' opened theatrically in North America on October 17, 1997.<ref name=bom>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=iknowwhatyoudidlastsummer.htm |title= I Know What You Did Last Summer (1997)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 8, 2018}}\n*[https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=iknowwhatyoudidlastsummer.htm Weekend] and [https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekly&id=iknowwhatyoudidlastsummer.htm weekly] data</ref> The film had been made on a $17&nbsp;million budget,{{sfn|Harper|2004|p=26}} yet already in its opening weekend it grossed $15,818,645 in 2,524 theaters in the United States and Canada, ranking number one; it remained in the number one position for an additional two weekends.<ref name=bom/> By the end of its theatrical run in December 1997, it had grossed $72,586,134 in the U.S. and Canada{{sfn|Harper|2004|p=26}} and $53&nbsp;million in other countries for a worldwide total of $126&nbsp;million.<ref name=numbers/><ref name=bom/>\n\nAccording to data compiled by ''[[Box Office Mojo]]'', ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' is the sixth highest-grossing slasher film as of 2019.<ref name=bom/>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film received mixed reviews upon release, inevitably drawing both positive and negative comparisons to ''Scream'', also written by Williamson. [[Mick LaSalle]] thought it inferior to ''Scream'',<ref>{{cite article| url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/FILM-REVIEW-Last-Summer-Offers-Thrills-But-2801119.php | title=FILM REVIEW -- 'Last Summer' Offers Thrills But No 'Scream' / Story starts strong, but turns formulaic | author=  Lasalle, Mick | work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]| date=October 17, 1997|access-date=July 5, 2017}}</ref> but Richard Harrington compared it favorably, stating that it was \"... a smart, sharply drawn genre film with a moral center and a solid cast of young actors to hold it.\"<ref>{{cite article| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/review97/iknowwhatyoudidlastsummerharr.htm | title='Summer' Time: The Living is Deadly | author=Harrington, Richard |work=The Washington Post | date=October 17, 1997 |access-date=July 5, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' was also enthusiastic, calling it a \"polished genre piece with superior fright elements that should perform at better than average theatrical levels.\"<ref>{{cite article| url=https://variety.com/1997/film/reviews/i-know-what-you-did-last-summer-111731125/| title=Review:'I Know What You Did Last Summer'|\n author=Elley, Derek | work=Variety | date=October 13, 1997 |access-date=July 4, 2015}}</ref> Critic [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film one of four stars and wrote in his review, \"The best shot in this film is the first one. Not a good sign.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19971017/REVIEWS/710170304/1023 |title=I Know What You Did Last Summer |author-link=Roger Ebert | first = Roger | last = Ebert |accessdate=November 11, 2017 |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]}}</ref> An ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' columnist praised Hewitt's performance, noting that Hewitt knows how to \"scream with soul.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,289974,00.html |title=Movie Review: 'I Know What You Did Last Summer' |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | access-date = June 9, 2011 |date=  October 24, 1997}}</ref>\n\nLawrence Van Gelder of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote of the film: \"This isn't real life. It's the [[Grand guignol|Grand Guignol]] of ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'', laying its claim to succeed ''Scream'' as a high-grossing, blood-drenched date-night crowd-pleaser. And why shouldn't it?\"<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Van Gelder, Lawrence|date=October 17, 1997|accessdate=April 7, 2018|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/library/film/101797summer-film-review.html|title=\"I Know What You Did Last Summer\": Creepy Guy, Ghost Stories, Teen-age Sex. Uh-Oh.}}</ref> James Kendrick of the ''Q Network'' wrote that 'Williamson's characters are all generic types, but they're still believable as people and they react realistically according to the situations,\" adding that the film was \"head and shoulders above earlier \"dead teenager movies.\"\"<ref>{{cite web|work=Q Network|author=Kendrick, James|title=Review: I Know What You Did Last Summer|archive-date=July 12, 2001|url-status=dead|url=http://www.qnetwork.com/movie/IKnowWhatYouDid.html|date=1998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010712212759/http://www.qnetwork.com/movie/IKnowWhatYouDid.html}}</ref> ''[[TV Guide]]''{{'}}s [[Maitland McDonagh]] awarded the film two out of five stars, noting: \"''Scream'' screenwriter Kevin Williamson takes a step back and writes the kind of movie ''Scream'' mocks. You can see him now, soaking up videos of ''[[Friday the 13th (1980 film)|Friday the 13th]]'' and ''[[Halloween (1978 film)|Halloween]]''\u2014not to mention the lesser likes of ''[[He Knows You're Alone]]'', ''[[Terror Train]]'', and ''[[My Bloody Valentine (film)|My Bloody Valentine]]''\u2014and saying, \"I can do that!\" And he can.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=[[TV Guide]]|author=McDonagh, Maitland|author-link=Maitland McDonagh|accessdate=November 22, 2017|url=http://www.tvguide.com/movies/i-know-what-you-did-last-summer/review/132622/|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer}}</ref>\n\nCritic [[James Berardinelli]] credited the film (along with ''Scream'') as igniting a new boom of slasher films, adding: \"There is one minor aspect of the plot that elevates ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' above the level of a typical '80s slasher flick -- it has an interesting subtext. I'm referring to the way the lives and friendships of these four individuals crumble in the wake of their accident. Guilt, confusion, and doubt build in them until they can no longer stand to be with each other or look at themselves in the mirror. Sadly, this potentially-fascinating element of the movie is dismissed quickly to facilitate a higher body count. And, as I said before, a few extra deaths can only make a slasher movie better, right?\"<ref>{{cite web|work=Reel Views|author=Berardinelli, James|author-link=James Berardinelli|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 12, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012010830/http://www.reelviews.net/movies/i/i_know.html|url=http://www.reelviews.net/movies/i/i_know.html|title=Review: I Know What You Did Last Summer|date=1997}}</ref>\n\nFilm scholar Adam Rockoff notes in his book ''Going to Pieces: The Rise and Fall of the Slasher Film, 1978\u20131986'' that at the time of its release, many critics branded ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' as an imitation of ''Scream''. However, he contends that it is a \"much different film,\" even in spite of the fact that their respective screenplays were penned by the same writer:\n\n{{quote|Whereas ''Scream'' relied heavily on self-conscious references and its pop culture veneer, ''Last Summer'' was a throwback to the slasher films of the early '80s. While, like ''Scream'', it employed the services of a group of young, sexy and almost impossibly good-looking actors, ''Last Summer'' played its horror straight. Those looking for a good old-fashioned slasher film were pleasantly surprised.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=182}} }}\n\nModern reception has continued to be mixed and on the review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a 42% approval rating, based on reviews from 66 critics. The consensus summarizes: \"A by-the-numbers slasher that arrived a decade too late, the mostly tedious ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' will likely only hook diehard fans of the genre.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/i_know_what_you_did_last_summer|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer (1997)|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=October 26, 2019}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] reported an aggregate score of 52 out of 100 based on reviews from 17 critics.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.metacritic.com/movie/i-know-what-you-did-last-summer | title=  I Know What You Did Last Summer|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | work = Metacritic | accessdate=  August 7, 2011}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B-\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer|work=Cinema Score|access-date=2018-08-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/|archive-date=2018-12-20|url-status=dead}} {{small|(Requires manual search)}}.</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Year\n!align=\"left\"|Ceremony\n!align=\"left\"|Category\n!align=\"left\"|Nominee\n!align=\"left\"|Result\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1997\n|align=\"left\"|[[ASCAP Award]]\n|align=\"left\"|Top Box Office Films\n|align=\"left\"|[[John Debney]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"left\"|1998\n|align=\"left\"|[[Saturn Award]]\n|align=\"left\"|Best Horror Film\n|align=\"left\"|''I Know What You Did Last Summer''\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" align=\"left\"|[[Blockbuster Entertainment Award]]\n|align=\"left\"|Favorite Female Newcomer\n| rowspan= \"2\" align=\"left\"|[[Jennifer Love Hewitt]]\n| rowspan= \"3\" {{Won}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Favorite Actress\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Favorite Supporting Actress \u2013 Horror\n|align=\"left\"|[[Sarah Michelle Gellar]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Favorite Actor \u2013 Horror\n|align=\"left\"|[[Freddie Prinze Jr.]]\n| rowspan= \"6\" {{Nom}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Favorite Actress \u2013 Horror\n|align=\"left\"|[[Jennifer Love Hewitt]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Favorite Supporting Actor\n|align=\"left\"|[[Ryan Phillippe]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[International Horror Guild Award]]\n|align=\"left\"|Best Movie\n|align=\"left\"|''I Know What You Did Last Summer''\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[MTV Movie Awards]]\n|align=\"left\"|Best Breakthrough Performance\n|align=\"left\"|[[Sarah Michelle Gellar]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Young Artist Award]]\n|align=\"left\"|Best Performance in a Feature Film \u2013 Leading Young Actress\n|align=\"left\"|[[Jennifer Love Hewitt]]\n|}\n\n==Music==\nThe film produced two soundtracks. One of them featured the score composed by [[John Debney]], while the other contained various rock songs found in the film.\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = I Know What You Did Last Summer: Original Motion Picture Score\n| type       = film\n| longtype   = ([[Music download|Digital download]])/Audio CD\n| artist     = [[John Debney]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 7, 1997\n| recorded   = 1997\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film score]]\n| length     = 50:44\n| label      = Super Tracks Music Group\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = I Know What You Did Last Summer: The Album\n| type       = soundtrack\n| longtype   = ([[Music download|Digital download]])/Audio CD\n| artist     = Various\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 7, 1997\n| recorded   = 1993\u2014June 1997\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]],<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/i-know-what-you-did-last-summer-mw0000028601|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer - Original Soundtrack|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=April 8, 2018}}</ref> [[alternative metal]]<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n| length     = 51:14\n| label      = [[Columbia Records]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed    = \n| headline     = \n| extra_column = Artist\n| title1= [[Hush (Billy Joe Royal song)|Hush]]\n| extra1= [[Kula Shaker]]\n| length1=2:55\n| title2=  [[Summer Breeze (song)|Summer Breeze]]\n| extra2= [[Type O Negative]] \n| length2= 4:57\n| title3= D.U.I.\n| extra3= [[The Offspring]] \n| length3= 2:26\n| title4= Kid\n| extra4= [[Green Apple Quick Step]] \n| length4= 3:17\n| title5= [[This Ain't the Summer of Love]]\" \n| extra5= [[L7 (band)|L7]] \n| length5=3:09\n| title6= Losin' It\n| extra6= [[Soul Asylum]]  \n| length6=3:01\n| title7=[[Hey Bulldog]]  \n| extra7= [[Toad the Wet Sprocket]] \n| length7=2:31\n| title8= My Baby's Got the Strangest Ways\n| extra8= [[Southern Culture on the Skids]]\n| length8=3:59\n| title9=Waterfall\n| extra9= [[The Din Pedals]]\n| length9=3:47\n| title10=[[Clumsy (Our Lady Peace song)|Clumsy]]\n| extra10= [[Our Lady Peace]] \n| length10=4:27\n| title11 = One Hundred Days\n| extra11= Flick  \n| length11=3:40\n| title12=Great Life\n| extra12= [[Goat (musician)|Goat]] \n| length12= 3:50\n| title13= 2Wicky\n| extra13= [[Hooverphonic]] \n| length13= 4:44\n| title14=Don't Mean Anything\n| extra14= [[Adam Cohen (musician)|Adam Cohen]] \n| length14= 3:43\n| title15= Proud\n| extra15= [[Korn]] \n| length15= 3:17\n}}\n\n'''Additional songs featured in the film (but not on a soundtrack):'''<ref>{{cite av media|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer|people=Gillespie, Jim (dir.)|series=(End credits)|year=1997|publisher=Columbia Pictures}}</ref>\n* \"Forgotten Too\" by Ugly Beauty \n* \"Wake Up Call\" by [[The Mighty Mighty Bosstones]]\n* \"[[In the Pines|Where Did You Sleep Last Night]]\" by [[Lead Belly]]\n* \"You're a Grand Old Flag\" by [[George M. Cohan]]\n* \"Beautiful Girl\" by [[Bing Crosby]]\n* \"Free\" by [[Ultra Nat\u00e9]]\n\n==Home media==\nThe film was released on DVD by [[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment|Columbia TriStar Home Video]] in the US on June 16, 1998. Special features included a theatrical trailer and filmmaker's commentary.<ref name=1998DVD>{{cite av media|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer|year=1998|orig-year=1997|asin= 6305017115|format=DVD|publisher=Columbia TriStar Home Video}}</ref>\n\nSony Pictures Home Entertainment released the film on [[Blu-ray]] for the first time on July 22, 2008, with additional special features including the director's short film, ''Joyride''.<ref name=2008blu>{{cite av media|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer|year=2008|orig-year=1997|asin= B0018CWWAU |format=Blu-ray|publisher=Sony Pictures Home Entertainment}}</ref> On September 30, 2014, [[Mill Creek Entertainment]] re-released the film on Blu-ray as a [[budget]] disc, featuring the film alone with no bonus materials.<ref name=2014blu>{{cite av media|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer|year=2014|orig-year=1997|asin= B00LU4URLC |format=Blu-ray|publisher=[[Mill Creek Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\n==Sequels and television series==\n{{Main|I Know What You Did Last Summer (franchise)}}\nThe film was followed by ''[[I Still Know What You Did Last Summer]]'' (1998) and ''[[I'll Always Know What You Did Last Summer]]'' (2006). In the first sequel, Jennifer Love Hewitt, Freddie Prinze Jr., and Muse Watson reprise their roles. The second sequel has very little relation to the first two, other than the premise, the villain, and the producers. It featured new characters and a different setting.\n \nOn July 26, 2019, it was announced that Amazon will develop a television series with [[Neal H. Moritz]] and [[James Wan]] producing, and Shay Hatten writing the pilot.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/tv/3575407/james-wan-directing-know-last-summer-pilot-amazon/|title=James Wan Directing 'I Know What You Did Last Summer' Pilot for Amazon!|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|date=July 26, 2019 |work=Bloody Disgusting|language=en|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n\n===Novels===\nIn 1973, Lois Duncan's ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' was published. It was republished as a tie-in to the film in 1997 and once again in 2018 with some of its content modernized. The film adaptation reenvisioned the story of the novel as a violent [[slasher film]], as opposed to the slow-burn mystery nature of the novel.\n\n===In popular culture===\n''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' has been referenced in various films and television series, and its central plot was [[parody|parodied]] at length in the spoof film ''[[Scary Movie]]'' (2000).{{sfn|Harper|2004|p=28}}\n\nIt was also spoofed in ''[[The Simpsons]]''{{'}} \"[[Treehouse of Horror X]]\" as \u201cI Know What You Diddily-Iddily-Did\u201d, with [[Ned Flanders]] as the killer.{{sfn|Murphy|2009|p=172}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-lr}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n* {{cite book|last=Fahy|first=Thomas, ed.|year=2010|title=The Philosophy of Horror|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|ref=harv|isbn=978-0-813-13954-8}}\n* {{anchor|Gillespie}}Gillespie, Jim; Mirkovich, Steve (1998). ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'': [[Audio commentary]] (DVD). Columbia TriStar Home Video.\n* {{cite book|last=Harper|first=Jim|year=2004|title=Legacy of Blood: A Comprehensive Guide to Slasher Movies|publisher=Critical Vision|ref=harv|isbn=978-1-900-48639-2}}\n* {{cite book|last=Murphy|first=Bernice|year=2009|title=The Suburban Gothic in American Popular Culture|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|ref=harv|isbn=978-0-230-21810-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rockoff|first=Adam|year=2016|title=Going to Pieces: The Rise and Fall of the Slasher Film, 1978\u20131986|publisher=Macmillan|ref=harv|isbn=978-0-786-49192-6}}\n* {{cite book|last=Shary|first=Timothy|year=2012|title=Teen Movies: American Youth on Screen|publisher=Columbia University Press|ref=harv|isbn=978-0-231-50160-6}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0119345}}\n* {{Amg movie|158841}}\n* {{mojo title|iknowwhatyoudidlastsummer}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|i_know_what_you_did_last_summer}}\n\n{{I Know What You Did Last Summer}}\n{{Lois Duncan}}\n{{Jim Gillespie}}\n{{Kevin Williamson}}\n\n[[Category:1997 films]]\n[[Category:1997 horror films]]\n[[Category:1990s horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:1990s serial killer films]]\n[[Category:1990s slasher films]]\n[[Category:1990s teen horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:American slasher films]]\n[[Category:American teen horror films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:American films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films about stalking]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on thriller novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on urban legends]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Neal H. Moritz]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1996]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1997]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1998]]\n[[Category:Films set in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films set in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Independence Day (United States) films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Mandalay Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Debney]]\n[[Category:I Know What You Did Last Summer|1]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jim Gillespie (director)]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Kevin Williamson]]\n[[Category:Holiday horror films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = I Know What You Did Last Summer\n| image          = I Know What You Did Last Summer.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jim Gillespie (director)|Jim Gillespie]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Neal H. Moritz]]\n* [[Erik Feig]]\n* Stokely Chaffin\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[Kevin Williamson (screenwriter)|Kevin Williamson]]\n| based on       = ''[[I Know What You Did Last Summer (novel)|I Know What You Did Last Summer]]''<br/>by [[Lois Duncan]]\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jennifer Love Hewitt]]\n* [[Sarah Michelle Gellar]]\n* [[Ryan Phillippe]]\n* [[Freddie Prinze Jr.]]\n* [[Johnny Galecki]]\n* [[Bridgette Wilson]]\n}}<!--PER POSTER BLOCK-->\n| music          = [[John Debney]]\n| cinematography = [[Denis Crossan]]\n| editing        = Steve Mirkovich\n| studio         = [[Mandalay Entertainment]]<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members//catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=60793|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer|work=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n| distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]<ref name=\"afi\" />\n| released       = {{filmdate|1997|10|17|ref1={{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=182}}}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $17 million<ref name=\"numbers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1997/IKNOW.php |title=I Know What You Did Last Summer - Box Office Data |work=The Numbers |accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref>{{sfn|Harper|2004|p=26}}\n| gross          = $125.2 million<ref name=\"numbers\" />\n}}\n\n'''''I Know What You Did Last Summer''''' is a  1997 American [[slasher film]] directed by [[Jim Gillespie (director)|Jim Gillespie]], written by [[Kevin Williamson (screenwriter)|Kevin Williamson]], and starring [[Jennifer Love Hewitt]], [[Sarah Michelle Gellar]], [[Ryan Phillippe]], and [[Freddie Prinze Jr.]]. Loosely based on [[I Know What You Did Last Summer (novel)|the 1973 novel of the same name]] by [[Lois Duncan]] and is the first installment in [[I Know What You Did Last Summer (film series)|''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' trilogy]]. The film centers on four young friends who are stalked by a hook-wielding killer one year after covering up a car accident in which they killed a man. The film also draws inspiration from the [[urban legend]] known as [[the Hook]].\n\nAfter having written ''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]'' (released the year prior), Williamson was approached to adapt Duncan's source novel by producer [[Erik Feig]]. Where Williamson's screenplay for ''Scream'' contained prominent elements of [[satire]] and self-referentiality, his adaptation of ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' reworked the novel's central plot to resemble a straightforward 1980s-era slasher film.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=183}} Shot on location in California and [[North Carolina]] in the spring of 1997, ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' was released theatrically in North America on October 17, 1997. It received mixed reviews from critics but was commercially successful, grossing $125 million worldwide on a budget of $17 million, and remaining number 1 at the U.S. [[box office]] for three consecutive weeks. It was also nominated for and won multiple awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0119345/awards |title=I Know What You Did Last Summer - Awards |publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]}}</ref>\n\nThe film was followed by two sequels, ''[[I Still Know What You Did Last Summer]]'' (1998) and ''[[I'll Always Know What You Did Last Summer]]'' (2006). ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' has also been parodied and referenced in popular culture,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Wayans Brothers' Comedy Style A Hit In 'Scary Movie' |journal=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]] |volume=98 |page=58 |date=August 14, 2000}}</ref> and credited alongside ''Scream'' with revitalizing the [[slasher film|slasher genre]] in the 1990s.{{sfn|Shary|2012|p=62}}\n\n==Plot==\nOn the [[Fourth of July]] in [[Southport, North Carolina]], Julie James and her friends Ray Bronson, Helen Shivers, and Barry Cox drive to the beach after attending a party. While driving along a coastal byway, they accidentally hit a pedestrian. Julie's friend Max passes by them on the road. Julie reassures Max that everything is all right, and he leaves. After some arguing, the group decides to dispose of the body, dumping it in the water. They agree to never discuss the incident again.\n\nA year later, Julie returns home from her college in [[Boston]] for the summer. Since the incident, the friends have gone their separate ways. Julie receives a letter with no return address, stating, \"I know what you did last summer!\" Disturbed, Julie tracks down Helen, who has returned to Southport to work at her family's department store after a failed attempt at an acting career in New York City. The girls take the note to Barry, who immediately suspects Max as he was the only person there that night. They confront Max on the docks, and Barry threatens him with a hook, even though Max claims he has no idea what Barry is talking about. Julie meets Ray, who is now working as a fisherman; he unsuccessfully tries to reconcile with her. Later, Max is killed by a figure in a [[raincoat|rain slicker]] wielding the same hook. Barry discovers a note in his gym locker saying, \"I know.\" He is then ambushed by the same assailant driving Barry's car.\n\nMeanwhile, as Ray still suspects Max, Julie researches newspaper articles which lead her to believe the man they ran over was a local named David Egan. Helen and Julie go to visit with David's sister Missy at her home. Missy explains to them that their family was devastated by David's death; she also mentions that a friend of David's named Billy Blue also visited her to pay his last respects. Later that night, the killer sneaks into Helen's house, cuts off most of her hair while she sleeps, and writes \"Soon\" in lipstick on her vanity mirror.\n\nThe following morning, Julie finds Max's corpse wearing Barry's stolen jacket in the trunk of her car. When she calls the others, the body is missing. Julie, Helen, and Barry confront Ray about the recent events. Ray claims to have received a threatening letter as well. Julie goes back to visit Missy, while Barry and Helen go to participate in the Fourth of July parade. Missy reveals David allegedly committed suicide out of guilt for the death of his girlfriend Susie in a car accident and shows David's suicide note to Julie. As the writing matches that of the note she received, Julie realizes it was not a suicide note, but a death threat.\n\nAt the Croaker Beauty Pageant, Helen witnesses Barry being murdered on the balcony. She rushes upstairs with a police officer but finds no sign of the killer or Barry. The officer escorts Helen home, but the killer lures him into an alley and murders him. Helen flees to her nearby family store, where her sister Elsa is closing for the night. The killer enters the store and murders Elsa. Helen is chased to the third floor of the building and escapes through a window, falling to a long alleyway. She manages to run toward the street, but the killer stops her and slashes her to death, her screams being drowned out by the sound of the oncoming parade.\n\nJulie finds an article mentioning Susie's father, Ben Willis, and realizes that Ben was the man they ran over, moments after he had killed David to avenge his daughter. She then goes to the docks to tell Ray, but he refuses to believe her. Julie notices Ray's boat is called ''Billy Blue'' and runs away. Ben appears, knocking Ray unconscious, and invites Julie to hide on his boat. On the boat, she finds photos and articles about her friends and her, and pictures of Susie. Ben's boat leaves the docks, and he begins tormenting Julie, chasing her below deck; there, she uncovers the bodies of Helen and Barry in the boat's ice box. Ray regains consciousness and steals a motorboat to rescue Julie. He ultimately uses the [[rigging]] to sever Ben's hand and send him overboard. When Julie and Ray are questioned by the police, they deny knowing why Ben attempted to kill them, but they are relieved not to have actually killed anyone the previous summer, and reconcile.\n\nA year later, Julie is in college in [[Boston]]. As she enters the shower, she notices the words \"I still know\" on the mirror. Moments later, the fisherman crashes through it as Julie screams in horror.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Jennifer Love Hewitt]] as Julie James\n* [[Sarah Michelle Gellar]] as Helen Shivers\n* [[Ryan Phillippe]] as Barry Cox\n* [[Freddie Prinze Jr.]] as Ray Bronson\n* [[Bridgette Wilson]] as Elsa Shivers\n* [[Anne Heche]] as Missy Egan\n* [[Muse Watson]] as Ben Willis/The Fisherman\n* [[Johnny Galecki]] as Max Neurick\n* [[Stuart Greer]] as Officer Caporizo\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and writing===\n''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' was a screenplay penned by Kevin Williamson several years beforehand, which was then rushed into production by Columbia Pictures upon the success of the Williamson-written ''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]'' (1996).<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.moviefone.com/2017/10/17/i-know-what-you-did-last-summer-movie-trivia/| title=14 Things You Never Know About 'I Know What You Did Last Summer'| author=Susman, Gary|work=MovieFone| date=October 17, 2017| access-date=February 19, 2018}}</ref> It was based on the [[I Know What You Did Last Summer (novel)|1973 novel of the same name]] by [[Lois Duncan]],{{sfn|Fahy|2010|p=248}} a youth-oriented suspense novel about four young people who are involved in a [[hit-and-run]] accident involving a young boy.<ref name=now/> Producer [[Erik Feig]] pitched the idea of a screen adaptation to [[Mandalay Entertainment]], and subsequently appointed Williamson to retool the core elements of Duncan's novel, rendering a screenplay more akin to a 1980s [[slasher film]].{{sfn|Harper|2004|p=26}}<ref name=now>{{cite av media|people=Gillis, Michael (prod., dir.)|medium=Documentary short|title=Now I Know What You Did Last Summer|year=2008|format=Blu-ray|work=I Know What You Did Last Summer|publisher=Sony Pictures Home Entertainment}}</ref> Inspired by his father, who had been a commercial fisherman, Williamson changed the setting of the novel to a small fishing village, and made the villain a hook-wielding fisherman.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=183}}\n\nThe killer's arming of himself with a hook is a reference to the [[urban legend]] \"[[The Hook]],\" which the four main characters recount at the beginning of the film around a campfire.<ref name=now/> According to Williamson, he wrote the scene as a way of indicating what was to come: \"Basically what I was doing was I was setting the framework to say, 'All right, audience: That's that legend. Now here's a new one.'\"<ref name=now/> Unlike Williamson's screenplay for the film's contemporary, ''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]'' (1996), which incorporated [[satire]] of the slasher film, ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' was written more as a straightforward slasher film.<ref name=now/>  Gillespie commented in 2008: \"The joy of this film for me as a filmmaker was in taking [the] elements that we've seen before, and saying to the audience: 'Here's something you've seen before'\u2014knowing that they're saying 'We've seen this before'\u2014and still getting them to jump.\"<ref name=now/> Gillespie also claimed that he felt Williamson's screenplay did not resemble a \"slasher horror movie,\" and that he saw it rather as simply \"a really good story\" with a [[morality]] tale embedded within it.<ref name=now/>\n\n===Pre-production===\nAccording to producer Stokely Chaffin, the producers sought out actors who were \"beautiful, but likable.\"<ref name=now/> Director Gillespie recalled that, though he had been unfamiliar with the screenplay's source material, that \"roughly 60 to 65%\" of the young women auditioning had read the novel as children.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:08:46)</ref> Jennifer Love Hewitt, who at the time was mainly known for her role on the television series ''[[Party of Five]]'', was cast in the lead of Julie James based on her \"ability to project vulnerability,\" which the producers, director Gillespie, and writer Williamson unanimously agreed upon.<ref name=now/> Initially, Hewitt was considered for the role of Helen.<ref name=now/> For the role of Barry, the crew had envisioned an actor with a \"{{convert|6|ft|2|in|abbr=on}} [[quarterback]]\" appearance, as the character had been written as an intimidating figure.<ref name=now/> Ryan Phillipe was ultimately cast in the part based on his audition, despite the fact that he was not as physically tall as the script had called for.<ref name=now/> Director Gillespie chose Freddie Prinze Jr. for the role of Ray, because he felt Prinze himself had an \"everyman\" quality much like the character.<ref name=now/>\n\nSarah Michelle Gellar was the last of the lead performers to be cast in the role of Helen.<ref name=now/> Like Hewitt, Gellar was also known to American audiences at the time for her roles in television, primarily as the titular [[Buffy Summers]] on ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]''.<ref name=now/> Gillespie commented on casting Gellar: \"I wanted an actress that had a warmth to her, but could still come off as being a bitch.\"<ref name=now/> For the supporting role of Missy, Gillespie sought an actress with significant screen presence, as the character, despite appearing in only two scenes, is central to several major plot points.<ref name=now/> Anne Heche was cast in the role, which she recalled as being two days' worth of work that required her to \"be scary.\"<ref name=now/>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Kolmer2.jpg|thumb|The cliff and rock shown at the beginning of the film, shot at Kolmer Gulch near [[Jenner, California]]]]\nScottish director Jim Gillespie was hired to direct the film after being suggested by writer Williamson.<ref name=\"now\" /> Star Hewitt would later state in 2008 that Gillespie was to date her \"favorite director [she's] ever worked with.\"<ref name=\"now\" /> Principal photography began on March 31, 1997{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}} and took place over a period of ten weeks<ref name=\"tenweeks\">[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:08:12)</ref> throughout the late spring-early summer of 1997.{{efn-lr|Gillespie notes in his 1998 audio commentary for the film that the California-shot scenes were filmed in June 1997.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:10:28)</ref> In the same commentary, he states that the shoot lasted ten weeks.<ref name=tenweeks/> According to Adam Rockoff, principal photography commenced on March 31, 1997.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}}}} Approximately seven weeks of the ten-week shoot took place at night, which Gillespie says was difficult for the cast and crew, and also created commotion in primary small-town locations in which they shot.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}} Gillespie devised a color scheme with cinematographer [[Denis Crossan]] which was marked by heavy [[blue]]s throughout, and a notable lack of bright colors.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:24:27)</ref> \n[[File:KolmerCurve.jpg|thumb|The blind curve where the car accident occurs early in the film, shot at Kolmer Gulch near [[Jenner, California]]]]\nFor the beginning of the film, coastal areas of [[Sonoma County, California]] stood in for North Carolina, where the film is set. The opening shots of the sun setting on a rugged coast were filmed at Kolmer Gulch, just north of the town of [[Jenner, California|Jenner]], on [[California State Route 1|Highway 1]].<ref name=locations>{{cite web| url=http://www.movie-locations.com/movies/i/I_Know_What_You_Did_Summer.html#.WoulM3tFzIU| title=Filming Locations for 'I Know What You Did Last Summer'| work=Movie-Locations.com| access-date=February 19, 2018}}</ref> The car crash scene was also filmed on Highway 1 in the same area. The scene in which the four friends are seated around a campfire on the beach next to a wrecked boat was inspired by a painting Gillespie had seen in a reference book; to achieve the image, the art department purchased an old boat in [[Bodega Bay]], cut it in half, and placed it at the beach location.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:09:58)</ref>\n[[File:Southport from the Water.JPG|thumb|The majority of the film was set in [[Southport, North Carolina]]. ]]\nThe remaining scenes were filmed primarily around the town of [[Southport, North Carolina|Southport]], [[North Carolina]].<ref name=locations/> Specific sites included the Amuzu Theater, where the beauty pageant is held, the Old Yacht Basin and Southport Fish Company.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.southport-oakisland.com/listing/i-know-what-you-did-last-summer-1997.html| title=I Know What You Did Last Summer (1997)| publisher= Southport-OakIsland.com| access-date=February 19, 2018}}</ref> Julie's house is on Short Street just north of Southport Marina.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.southporttimes.com/featured/200407.html| title=Movies Filmed in Southport, North Carolina| work=Southport Times| access-date=February 19, 2018}}</ref> The daytime sequences shot on the marina show multiple vessels traversing the water; though real vessels, the boat traffic was orchestrated by a marine traffic coordinator to make the waterway appear lively.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:36:57)</ref> The Shivers Department Store setting in the film was discovered on location in Southport by director Gillespie, who was so impressed by the location that he reworked elements of the script in order to incorporate it into the film; it eventually became the primary setting for Helen's extended chase sequence with the killer.<ref name=now/> The exterior sequences of Julie's Boston college campus were in fact shot at [[Duke University]],<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:24:51)</ref> while the hospital sequence was filmed at Southport's [[Dosher Memorial Hospital]] in an unused wing of the hospital.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (0:43:00)</ref>\n\nThe final sequence on the boat was shot on an actual water-bound vessel on the [[Cape Fear River]], which proved difficult for the actors and crew.<ref name=now/> According to Gillespie, the filmmakers nearly lost the boat while attempting to dock it due to the volatile waters, after which they were forced to leave and shoot other footage until the following day.<ref name=now/>\n\n===Post-production===\nGillespie chose to film virtually no onscreen blood as he did not want the film to be overly gratuitous in terms of violence.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}}<ref name=now/> The scene in which Elsa has her throat slashed while standing against a glass door had originally been shot from behind without any blood appearing on the glass. However, producer Feig worried that the scene appeared \"medically impossible,\" after which Gillespie re-shot it (post-principal photography) with a visual effect of blood spattering across the glass.<ref name=now/> Upon test screenings of the film, Gillespie and the producers decided that a death sequence needed to occur earlier in the film to establish a sense of legitimate danger for the main characters.<ref name=now/> The scene in which Max is murdered in the crab factory was subsequently filmed and implemented into the final cut to achieve this (in the original script, his character was not killed).<ref name=now/>\n\nThe original ending of the film featured a sequence in which Julie receives an [[email]] reading: \"I Still Know.\"{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}} This ending was scrapped for the more dramatic ending featured in the final cut of the film, in which Julie finds the same message scrawled on a shower stall just before the killer comes crashing through the glass.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}} This footage was also shot after principal photography, on a soundstage next-door to where Hewitt was filming ''Party of Five''.<ref>[[#Gillespie|Gillespie & Mirkovich 1998]] (1:35:29)</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Marketing===\nIn anticipation of the film's release, distributor [[Columbia Pictures]] began a summer marketing campaign that presented the film as being \"From the creator of ''Scream''.\"{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}} [[Miramax|Miramax Films]] subsequently filed a lawsuit against Columbia, arguing the claim was inaccurate as the director of ''Scream'' was [[Wes Craven]], not Williamson.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=184}} The week following the film's theatrical release, a federal judge awarded Miramax an [[injunction]] requiring that Columbia remove the claim from their advertising campaign.<ref>{{cite web|work=Variety|url=https://variety.com/1997/biz/news/miramax-reigns-in-court-1116674228/|title=Miramax reigns in court|date=October 20, 1997|accessdate=April 8, 2018|author=Karon, Paul}}</ref> Williamson had requested its removal prior after seeing it on a theater poster.<ref name=lawsuit>{{cite web|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/mar/07/business/fi-26323|title=Miramax Wins 'Scream' Claim Against Sony|author=Bates, James|date=March 7, 1998|accessdate=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMiramax won a subsequent lawsuit against Columbia during a March 1998 hearing. In a press release, executive [[Bob Weinstein]] noted plans to \"vigorously pursue\" damage claims against Columbia Pictures for their use of the claim.<ref name=lawsuit/>\n\n===Box office===\n''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' opened theatrically in North America on October 17, 1997.<ref name=bom>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=iknowwhatyoudidlastsummer.htm |title= I Know What You Did Last Summer (1997)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 8, 2018}}\n*[https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=iknowwhatyoudidlastsummer.htm Weekend] and [https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekly&id=iknowwhatyoudidlastsummer.htm weekly] data</ref> The film had been made on a $17&nbsp;million budget,{{sfn|Harper|2004|p=26}} yet already in its opening weekend it grossed $15,818,645 in 2,524 theaters in the United States and Canada, ranking number one; it remained in the number one position for an additional two weekends.<ref name=bom/> By the end of its theatrical run in December 1997, it had grossed $72,586,134 in the U.S. and Canada{{sfn|Harper|2004|p=26}} and $53&nbsp;million in other countries for a worldwide total of $126&nbsp;million.<ref name=numbers/><ref name=bom/>\n\nAccording to data compiled by ''[[Box Office Mojo]]'', ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' is the sixth highest-grossing slasher film as of 2019.<ref name=bom/>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film received mixed reviews upon release, inevitably drawing both positive and negative comparisons to ''Scream'', also written by Williamson. [[Mick LaSalle]] thought it inferior to ''Scream'',<ref>{{cite article| url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/FILM-REVIEW-Last-Summer-Offers-Thrills-But-2801119.php | title=FILM REVIEW -- 'Last Summer' Offers Thrills But No 'Scream' / Story starts strong, but turns formulaic | author=  Lasalle, Mick | work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]| date=October 17, 1997|access-date=July 5, 2017}}</ref> but Richard Harrington compared it favorably, stating that it was \"... a smart, sharply drawn genre film with a moral center and a solid cast of young actors to hold it.\"<ref>{{cite article| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/review97/iknowwhatyoudidlastsummerharr.htm | title='Summer' Time: The Living is Deadly | author=Harrington, Richard |work=The Washington Post | date=October 17, 1997 |access-date=July 5, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' was also enthusiastic, calling it a \"polished genre piece with superior fright elements that should perform at better than average theatrical levels.\"<ref>{{cite article| url=https://variety.com/1997/film/reviews/i-know-what-you-did-last-summer-111731125/| title=Review:'I Know What You Did Last Summer'|\n author=Elley, Derek | work=Variety | date=October 13, 1997 |access-date=July 4, 2015}}</ref> Critic [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film one of four stars and wrote in his review, \"The best shot in this film is the first one. Not a good sign.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19971017/REVIEWS/710170304/1023 |title=I Know What You Did Last Summer |author-link=Roger Ebert | first = Roger | last = Ebert |accessdate=November 11, 2017 |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]}}</ref> An ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' columnist praised Hewitt's performance, noting that Hewitt knows how to \"scream with soul.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,289974,00.html |title=Movie Review: 'I Know What You Did Last Summer' |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | access-date = June 9, 2011 |date=  October 24, 1997}}</ref>\n\nLawrence Van Gelder of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote of the film: \"This isn't real life. It's the [[Grand guignol|Grand Guignol]] of ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'', laying its claim to succeed ''Scream'' as a high-grossing, blood-drenched date-night crowd-pleaser. And why shouldn't it?\"<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Van Gelder, Lawrence|date=October 17, 1997|accessdate=April 7, 2018|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/library/film/101797summer-film-review.html|title=\"I Know What You Did Last Summer\": Creepy Guy, Ghost Stories, Teen-age Sex. Uh-Oh.}}</ref> James Kendrick of the ''Q Network'' wrote that 'Williamson's characters are all generic types, but they're still believable as people and they react realistically according to the situations,\" adding that the film was \"head and shoulders above earlier \"dead teenager movies.\"\"<ref>{{cite web|work=Q Network|author=Kendrick, James|title=Review: I Know What You Did Last Summer|archive-date=July 12, 2001|url-status=dead|url=http://www.qnetwork.com/movie/IKnowWhatYouDid.html|date=1998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010712212759/http://www.qnetwork.com/movie/IKnowWhatYouDid.html}}</ref> ''[[TV Guide]]''{{'}}s [[Maitland McDonagh]] awarded the film two out of five stars, noting: \"''Scream'' screenwriter Kevin Williamson takes a step back and writes the kind of movie ''Scream'' mocks. You can see him now, soaking up videos of ''[[Friday the 13th (1980 film)|Friday the 13th]]'' and ''[[Halloween (1978 film)|Halloween]]''\u2014not to mention the lesser likes of ''[[He Knows You're Alone]]'', ''[[Terror Train]]'', and ''[[My Bloody Valentine (film)|My Bloody Valentine]]''\u2014and saying, \"I can do that!\" And he can.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=[[TV Guide]]|author=McDonagh, Maitland|author-link=Maitland McDonagh|accessdate=November 22, 2017|url=http://www.tvguide.com/movies/i-know-what-you-did-last-summer/review/132622/|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer}}</ref>\n\nCritic [[James Berardinelli]] credited the film (along with ''Scream'') as igniting a new boom of slasher films, adding: \"There is one minor aspect of the plot that elevates ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' above the level of a typical '80s slasher flick -- it has an interesting subtext. I'm referring to the way the lives and friendships of these four individuals crumble in the wake of their accident. Guilt, confusion, and doubt build in them until they can no longer stand to be with each other or look at themselves in the mirror. Sadly, this potentially-fascinating element of the movie is dismissed quickly to facilitate a higher body count. And, as I said before, a few extra deaths can only make a slasher movie better, right?\"<ref>{{cite web|work=Reel Views|author=Berardinelli, James|author-link=James Berardinelli|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 12, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012010830/http://www.reelviews.net/movies/i/i_know.html|url=http://www.reelviews.net/movies/i/i_know.html|title=Review: I Know What You Did Last Summer|date=1997}}</ref>\n\nFilm scholar Adam Rockoff notes in his book ''Going to Pieces: The Rise and Fall of the Slasher Film, 1978\u20131986'' that at the time of its release, many critics branded ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' as an imitation of ''Scream''. However, he contends that it is a \"much different film,\" even in spite of the fact that their respective screenplays were penned by the same writer:\n\n{{quote|Whereas ''Scream'' relied heavily on self-conscious references and its pop culture veneer, ''Last Summer'' was a throwback to the slasher films of the early '80s. While, like ''Scream'', it employed the services of a group of young, sexy and almost impossibly good-looking actors, ''Last Summer'' played its horror straight. Those looking for a good old-fashioned slasher film were pleasantly surprised.{{sfn|Rockoff|2016|p=182}} }}\n\nModern reception has continued to be mixed and on the review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a 42% approval rating, based on reviews from 66 critics. The consensus summarizes: \"A by-the-numbers slasher that arrived a decade too late, the mostly tedious ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' will likely only hook diehard fans of the genre.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/i_know_what_you_did_last_summer|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer (1997)|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=October 26, 2019}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] reported an aggregate score of 52 out of 100 based on reviews from 17 critics.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.metacritic.com/movie/i-know-what-you-did-last-summer | title=  I Know What You Did Last Summer|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | work = Metacritic | accessdate=  August 7, 2011}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B-\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer|work=Cinema Score|access-date=2018-08-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/|archive-date=2018-12-20|url-status=dead}} {{small|(Requires manual search)}}.</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Year\n!align=\"left\"|Ceremony\n!align=\"left\"|Category\n!align=\"left\"|Nominee\n!align=\"left\"|Result\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1997\n|align=\"left\"|[[ASCAP Award]]\n|align=\"left\"|Top Box Office Films\n|align=\"left\"|[[John Debney]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"left\"|1998\n|align=\"left\"|[[Saturn Award]]\n|align=\"left\"|Best Horror Film\n|align=\"left\"|''I Know What You Did Last Summer''\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" align=\"left\"|[[Blockbuster Entertainment Award]]\n|align=\"left\"|Favorite Female Newcomer\n| rowspan= \"2\" align=\"left\"|[[Jennifer Love Hewitt]]\n| rowspan= \"3\" {{Won}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Favorite Actress\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Favorite Supporting Actress \u2013 Horror\n|align=\"left\"|[[Sarah Michelle Gellar]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Favorite Actor \u2013 Horror\n|align=\"left\"|[[Freddie Prinze Jr.]]\n| rowspan= \"6\" {{Nom}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Favorite Actress \u2013 Horror\n|align=\"left\"|[[Jennifer Love Hewitt]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Favorite Supporting Actor\n|align=\"left\"|[[Ryan Phillippe]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[International Horror Guild Award]]\n|align=\"left\"|Best Movie\n|align=\"left\"|''I Know What You Did Last Summer''\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[MTV Movie Awards]]\n|align=\"left\"|Best Breakthrough Performance\n|align=\"left\"|[[Sarah Michelle Gellar]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Young Artist Award]]\n|align=\"left\"|Best Performance in a Feature Film \u2013 Leading Young Actress\n|align=\"left\"|[[Jennifer Love Hewitt]]\n|}\n\n==Music==\nThe film produced two soundtracks. One of them featured the score composed by [[John Debney]], while the other contained various rock songs found in the film.\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = I Know What You Did Last Summer: Original Motion Picture Score\n| type       = film\n| longtype   = ([[Music download|Digital download]])/Audio CD\n| artist     = [[John Debney]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 7, 1997\n| recorded   = 1997\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film score]]\n| length     = 50:44\n| label      = Super Tracks Music Group\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = I Know What You Did Last Summer: The Album\n| type       = soundtrack\n| longtype   = ([[Music download|Digital download]])/Audio CD\n| artist     = Various\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 7, 1997\n| recorded   = 1993\u2014June 1997\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]],<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/i-know-what-you-did-last-summer-mw0000028601|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer - Original Soundtrack|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=April 8, 2018}}</ref> [[alternative metal]]<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n| length     = 51:14\n| label      = [[Columbia Records]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed    = \n| headline     = \n| extra_column = Artist\n| title1= [[Hush (Billy Joe Royal song)|Hush]]\n| extra1= [[Kula Shaker]]\n| length1=2:55\n| title2=  [[Summer Breeze (song)|Summer Breeze]]\n| extra2= [[Type O Negative]] \n| length2= 4:57\n| title3= D.U.I.\n| extra3= [[The Offspring]] \n| length3= 2:26\n| title4= Kid\n| extra4= [[Green Apple Quick Step]] \n| length4= 3:17\n| title5= [[This Ain't the Summer of Love]]\" \n| extra5= [[L7 (band)|L7]] \n| length5=3:09\n| title6= Losin' It\n| extra6= [[Soul Asylum]]  \n| length6=3:01\n| title7=[[Hey Bulldog]]  \n| extra7= [[Toad the Wet Sprocket]] \n| length7=2:31\n| title8= My Baby's Got the Strangest Ways\n| extra8= [[Southern Culture on the Skids]]\n| length8=3:59\n| title9=Waterfall\n| extra9= [[The Din Pedals]]\n| length9=3:47\n| title10=[[Clumsy (Our Lady Peace song)|Clumsy]]\n| extra10= [[Our Lady Peace]] \n| length10=4:27\n| title11 = One Hundred Days\n| extra11= Flick  \n| length11=3:40\n| title12=Great Life\n| extra12= [[Goat (musician)|Goat]] \n| length12= 3:50\n| title13= 2Wicky\n| extra13= [[Hooverphonic]] \n| length13= 4:44\n| title14=Don't Mean Anything\n| extra14= [[Adam Cohen (musician)|Adam Cohen]] \n| length14= 3:43\n| title15= Proud\n| extra15= [[Korn]] \n| length15= 3:17\n}}\n\n'''Additional songs featured in the film (but not on a soundtrack):'''<ref>{{cite av media|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer|people=Gillespie, Jim (dir.)|series=(End credits)|year=1997|publisher=Columbia Pictures}}</ref>\n* \"Forgotten Too\" by Ugly Beauty \n* \"Wake Up Call\" by [[The Mighty Mighty Bosstones]]\n* \"[[In the Pines|Where Did You Sleep Last Night]]\" by [[Lead Belly]]\n* \"You're a Grand Old Flag\" by [[George M. Cohan]]\n* \"Beautiful Girl\" by [[Bing Crosby]]\n* \"Free\" by [[Ultra Nat\u00e9]]\n\n==Home media==\nThe film was released on DVD by [[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment|Columbia TriStar Home Video]] in the US on June 16, 1998. Special features included a theatrical trailer and filmmaker's commentary.<ref name=1998DVD>{{cite av media|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer|year=1998|orig-year=1997|asin= 6305017115|format=DVD|publisher=Columbia TriStar Home Video}}</ref>\n\nSony Pictures Home Entertainment released the film on [[Blu-ray]] for the first time on July 22, 2008, with additional special features including the director's short film, ''Joyride''.<ref name=2008blu>{{cite av media|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer|year=2008|orig-year=1997|asin= B0018CWWAU |format=Blu-ray|publisher=Sony Pictures Home Entertainment}}</ref> On September 30, 2014, [[Mill Creek Entertainment]] re-released the film on Blu-ray as a [[budget]] disc, featuring the film alone with no bonus materials.<ref name=2014blu>{{cite av media|title=I Know What You Did Last Summer|year=2014|orig-year=1997|asin= B00LU4URLC |format=Blu-ray|publisher=[[Mill Creek Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\n==Sequels and television series==\n{{Main|I Know What You Did Last Summer (franchise)}}\nThe film was followed by ''[[I Still Know What You Did Last Summer]]'' (1998) and ''[[I'll Always Know What You Did Last Summer]]'' (2006). In the first sequel, Jennifer Love Hewitt, Freddie Prinze Jr., and Muse Watson reprise their roles. The second sequel has very little relation to the first two, other than the premise, the villain, and the producers. It featured new characters and a different setting.\n \nOn July 26, 2019, it was announced that Amazon will develop a television series with [[Neal H. Moritz]] and [[James Wan]] producing, and Shay Hatten writing the pilot.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/tv/3575407/james-wan-directing-know-last-summer-pilot-amazon/|title=James Wan Directing 'I Know What You Did Last Summer' Pilot for Amazon!|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|date=July 26, 2019 |work=Bloody Disgusting|language=en|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n\n===Novels===\nIn 1973, Lois Duncan's ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' was published. It was republished as a tie-in to the film in 1997 and once again in 2018 with some of its content modernized. The film adaptation reenvisioned the story of the novel as a violent [[slasher film]], as opposed to the slow-burn mystery nature of the novel.\n\n===In popular culture===\n''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' has been referenced in various films and television series, and its central plot was [[parody|parodied]] at length in the spoof film ''[[Scary Movie]]'' (2000).{{sfn|Harper|2004|p=28}}\n\nIt was also spoofed in ''[[The Simpsons]]''{{'}} \"[[Treehouse of Horror X]]\" as \u201cI Know What You Diddily-Iddily-Did\u201d, with [[Ned Flanders]] as the killer.{{sfn|Murphy|2009|p=172}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-lr}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n* {{cite book|last=Fahy|first=Thomas, ed.|year=2010|title=The Philosophy of Horror|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|ref=harv|isbn=978-0-813-13954-8}}\n* {{anchor|Gillespie}}Gillespie, Jim; Mirkovich, Steve (1998). ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'': [[Audio commentary]] (DVD). Columbia TriStar Home Video.\n* {{cite book|last=Harper|first=Jim|year=2004|title=Legacy of Blood: A Comprehensive Guide to Slasher Movies|publisher=Critical Vision|ref=harv|isbn=978-1-900-48639-2}}\n* {{cite book|last=Murphy|first=Bernice|year=2009|title=The Suburban Gothic in American Popular Culture|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|ref=harv|isbn=978-0-230-21810-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rockoff|first=Adam|year=2016|title=Going to Pieces: The Rise and Fall of the Slasher Film, 1978\u20131986|publisher=Macmillan|ref=harv|isbn=978-0-786-49192-6}}\n* {{cite book|last=Shary|first=Timothy|year=2012|title=Teen Movies: American Youth on Screen|publisher=Columbia University Press|ref=harv|isbn=978-0-231-50160-6}}\n\n==External links==\n{